The paper deals with the intersection of database theory and information theory, specifically focusing on conjunctive and disjunctive datalog rules and their output size bounds. This suggests that cs.DB (Databases) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also introduces a new algorithm called PANDA, which is based on submodular width and fractional hypertree width, indicating that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) are also relevant sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses proof sequences for Shannon flow inequalities, which could fall under cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
